Let \( P \) be the field point on the axis of the disc at a distance \( z \) from the origin. Consider a ring of radius \( r \) and width \( dr \). The charge on the ring is \( dq = 2\pi r \, dr \, \sigma \) where \( \sigma \) is the charge density (charge per unit area), as shown in Fig. 11.25.

The electric field at \( P \) can be resolved into a component along the \( z \)-axis and a component perpendicular to it. The perpendicular components, when added, become zero due to symmetry. The components along the \( z \)-axis are added as follows:

\[
dE_{||} = \frac{dq \, z}{4\pi \varepsilon_0 (z^2 + r^2)^{3/2}} = \frac{2\pi r \, dr \, \sigma \, z}{4\pi \varepsilon_0 (z^2 + r^2)^{3/2}}
\]

The total electric field \( E \) at point \( P \) is given by integrating \( dE_{||} \):

\[
E = \int dE_{||} = \frac{\sigma}{2\varepsilon_0} z \int_0^R \frac{r \, dr}{(z^2 + r^2)^{3/2}}
\]

Evaluating the integral, we find:

\[
E = \frac{\sigma}{2\varepsilon_0} \left( 1 - \frac{z}{(z^2 + R^2)^{1/2}} \right)
\]

