\begin{equation}
    u = \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_0 E^2 = \frac{q^2}{8 \pi^2 \varepsilon_0 l^2 r^2}
\end{equation}
where we have used equation (1). The energy stored between the coaxial cylinders of length \( l \) and radii \( R \) and \( a \) is
\begin{equation}
    U = \int u \, dv = \int_a^R u (2 \pi r l) \, dr
\end{equation}
where \( dv = (2 \pi r \, dr) l \) is the volume element. Using equation (2) in equation (3), we have
\begin{align}
    U &= \frac{q^2}{4 \pi \varepsilon_0 l} \int_a^R \frac{dr}{r} \\
    &= \frac{q^2}{4 \pi \varepsilon_0 l} \ln \frac{R}{a}
\end{align}

Similarly, the energy stored between the coaxial cylinders of radii \( b \) and \( a \) is
\begin{equation}
    U_0 = \frac{q^2}{4 \pi \varepsilon_0 l} \ln \frac{b}{a}
\end{equation}

Thus, the ratio of energies is
\begin{equation}
    \frac{U}{U_0} = \frac{\ln(R/a)}{\ln(b/a)}
\end{equation}

